09:35 <Enygma`> tmortagne: any idea about this http://ci.xwiki.org/job/xwiki-enterprise-test-escaping/6/ ?  
09:36 <Enygma`> they are failing since yesterday, apparently caused by one of your 2 commits on http://ci.xwiki.org/job/xwiki-platform/8/  
09:36 <tmortagne> Enygma`: I saw it but I don't see how it could be related to the commit jenkins say it's related  
09:37 <Enygma`> not sure either  
09:37 <tmortagne> the commit just adds test for null object/properties  
09:38 <tmortagne> do you reproduce it locally ?  
09:38 <Enygma`> trying now  
09:38 <tmortagne> (currently working on ghost localization bundles)  
09:45 <mflorea> has joined #xwiki  
09:46 <Enygma`> yes, I`ve tried your latest commits. Only the initial solr + lucene threads make noise when deleting a wiki. After that, all other page access logs are ok  
09:46 <Enygma`> so it`s better and enough, IMO, for the RC1  
09:48 <tmortagne> Enygma`: the log you have with "the initial solr + lucene threads" should not be related to localization  
09:49 <tmortagne> SOLR itself fail to load document it been asked to index  
09:49 <Enygma`> agreed. will create a new issue about that separately.  
09:50 <tmortagne> I think there is one  
09:50 <tmortagne> it's not new  
09:51 <Enygma`> will do a quick search for it  
09:52 <tmortagne> Enygma`: I found what was the issue...  
09:52 <tmortagne> let me give you a link  
09:53 <tmortagne> https://github.com/xwiki/xwiki-platform/blob/master/xwiki-platform-core/xwiki-platform-watchlist/xwiki-platform-watchlist-ui/src/main/resources/XWiki/WatchListTranslations.xml#L76  
09:53 <tmortagne> this bundle is global  
09:54 <tmortagne> which mean it's registered on the root CM, that's the one staying when the wiki is deleted (and the wiki CM cleaned)  
09:54 <tmortagne> fixing it and thinking of a way to handle better this use case (in the rare case it's valid)  
09:57 <Enygma`> so global bundles need to be removed as well in the event that their document or their wiki gets deleted (if they are not on the main wiki)  
09:59 <Enygma`> we really need to fix the solr logs  
09:59 <Enygma`> when xwiki is closed before solr gets to index or when a wiki is deleted before sorl indexes, etc  
09:59 <Enygma`> well, not the logs, but the index thread  
10:00 <Enygma`> I`m getting solr logs in tests when the instance is closed after a test is done

11:21 <vmassol> guys I'm going to upgrade our selenium version  
11:21 <vmassol> we have several "Unable to bind to locking port 7054 within 45000 ms" errros  
11:21 <vmassol> and I think it's caused by our selenium version  
11:21 <vmassol> according to https://code.google.com/p/selenium/issues/detail?id=7272 it's been fixed on 24 of June 2014  
11:22 <vmassol> we're using version 2.40.0 but there's now 2.42.2 with lots of fixes  
11:23 <vmassol> Enygma`: ok?  
11:23 <lucaa> has joined #xwiki  
11:25 <KermitTheFragger> has joined #xwiki  
11:30 <vmassol> ok doing it and I'll revert if need be

12:10 <Enygma`> vmassol: I guess we`ll have(/be able) to update our Firefox version as well, if this Selenium version is ok.  
12:10 <evalica> has joined #xwiki  
12:10 <vmassol> well we're supposed to support the latest FF version indeed  
12:10 <vmassol> right now we have 27 installed on agents  
12:11 <vmassol> what's the latest FF?  
12:11 <vmassol> (I use chrome)  
12:11 <Enygma`> running 31.0 on my machine  
12:11 <vmassol> anyway let's not do everything at the same time ;) I suggest we release RC1 first  
12:12 <tmortagne> latest in 32  
12:12 <vmassol> I see selenium 2.42.0 supports native events for FF28 only  
12:12 <tmortagne> s/in/is/  
12:12 <tmortagne> maybe they did not changed since 28  
12:13 <vmassol> so apparently in the release notes there's no mention of anything newer than 28  
12:13 <vmassol> https://code.google.com/p/selenium/source/browse/java/CHANGELOG  
12:14 <vmassol> in the past there was always a mention in the RN when native event support was added for a given FF version  
12:14 <vmassol> right now I wouldn't use a version newer than 28  
12:14 <vmassol> I even suggest we stay on 27 FTM  
12:14 <vmassol> till the next release of selenium  
12:16 <tmortagne> vmassol: http://docs.seleniumhq.org/about/platforms.jsp  
12:16 <tmortagne> for the official support doc  
12:17 <vmassol> ok same as release notes  
12:17 <vmassol> RN are more precise actually  
12:18 <tmortagne> sure but at least now we know the next version should work with more recent FF version

13:11 <Enygma`> hmm, on a better inspection on the templates that are failing the test it seems that they are indeed producing an empty result  
13:11 <Enygma`> but that is just because of the way they are written  
13:12 <Enygma`> it seems that these tests expect a result, but these templates (skins/flamingo/menus\_macros.vm, skins/flamingo/menus\_wiki.vm, skins/flamingo/menus\_home.vm) simply produce none when taken outside their intended context (like these tests are doing)

13:39 <Enygma`> I meant: "Edit the release-translations.sh file to set branch, if needed.:"

13:41 <Enygma`> ignoring it

14:33 <Enygma`> guys, when releasing a RC1 (6.2-rc-1), I am asked "What is the next SNAPSHOT version?" and "6.3-SNAPSHOT" is suggested  
14:33 <Enygma`> then it asks me to create a stable branch  
14:33 <vmassol> 6.2-SNAPSHOT is the next version  
14:33 <Enygma`> and then it ask me "What is the next master version?", suggesting "6.3-SNAPSHOT"  
14:34 <Enygma`> right... so that is for the stable branch, the first question  
14:34 <vmassol> master is indeed 6.3-SNAPSHOT  
14:34 <Enygma`> it`s a bit confusing  
14:34 <Enygma`> canceling and restarting, since I pressed enter at the first question  
14:35 <Enygma`> thanks  
14:36 <tmortagne> yes that's because release plugin always increment the last number for next SNAPSHOT  
14:37 <tmortagne> it's not very clever for use case like this
